      <bioghist id="aspace_ffe9f74d3b4f2a610c172fbe3ddc5ccc">
         <head>HENRY KISSINGER (1923-2023)</head>
         <p>Henry Alfred Kissinger was born Heinz Alfred Kissinger on May 27, 1923, in Fürth, Germany, and immigrated to the United States in 1938. After studying at Harvard University, he joined the faculty as a member of the Department of Government and made a reputation for his scholarly work on international affairs, which included his best-selling book <title>
               <part>Nuclear Weapons and Foreign Policy</part>
            </title> (1957).</p>
         <p>Kissinger later served as assistant to the president for national security affairs (national security advisor) from 1969 to 1975, and as Secretary of State from 1973 to 1977 under presidents Richard Nixon and Gerald Ford. In office, he was known especially for his work on normalizing relations with China, a detente with the Soviet Union, peace negotiations during the Vietnam War, and his Middle East shuttle diplomacy.</p>
         <p>After leaving office, Kissinger remained an influential author and commentator on foreign affairs and founded the international consulting firm Kissinger Associates.</p>
      </bioghist>
      <bioghist id="aspace_10ce91adc81897d50e3e2964aaec3b50">
         <head>HANS MORGENTHAU (1904-1980)</head>
         <p>Hans Morgenthau (1904-1980) was a political scientist, political advisor, historian, and jurist. He was born in Coburg, Germany and attend the Universities of Berlin, Frankfurt, and Munich. Morgenthau continued his postgraduate education at the Graduate Institute for International Studies in Geneva, Switzerland.</p>
         <p>He taught and practiced law in Germany, Spain, and Switzerland before immigrating to the United States in 1937 to escape Hitler's rise to power; he subsequently became a naturalized citizen in 1943. Morgenthau taught at several universities in the United States including Brooklyn College, the University of Missouri-Kansas City, the University of Chicago, the City College of New York, and The New School.</p>
         <p>Morgenthau frequently published work about political theory and is most known for his book, <title>
               <part>Politics Among Nations</part>
            </title>--published in 1948--which outlines the concepts of realism, power, and national interest in international politics. It became a staple text in international relations studies. Morgenthau was also a vocal analyst of American politics. He was a consultant for the Kennedy administration and later became a dissenter of the Vietnam War.</p>
      </bioghist>
